Mozambique's former finance minister, Manuel Chang, is awaiting a court decision on whether he will be extradited to his home country or the United States. Mozambican human rights defender Professor Adriano Nuvunga speaks to #eNCA Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Mozambique's former finance minister, Manuel Chang, is awaiting a court decision on whether he will be extradited to his home country or the United States. Chang has been in custody in South Africa since 2018. He is alleged to have signed the illegal sovereign guarantees allowing the contracting of $2 billion, also known as the 'hidden debt'. READ:Â Mozambique ex-minister to be extradited to US for fraud trial In November the High Court in Johannesburg overturned the decision of Justice Minister Ronald Lamola to extradite Chang to Mozambique and ordered that Chang be extradited to the US instead. However, the Mozambican government has since brought an appeal directly to the South African Constitutional Court, as well as an application for leave to appeal to the High Court. Meanwhile, Chang remains in a South African prison. Watch the video above for more details on this story